b:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 mb-6 not-prose","children":["$","ul",null,{"className":"space-y-2.5 border-l-4 border-yellow-400/50 pl-4","children":[["$","li","0",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Seoul researchers develop flat wearable power source"}]]}],["$","li","1",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Heat flows sideways through thin films"}]]}],["$","li","2",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Smart clothing could finally go battery-free"}]]}]]}]}]
c:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 article-prose max-w-none","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":["For anyone who's had their fitness tracker die mid-run, Seoul National University's latest research hits close to home. The team has developed a completely flat, wearable power source that generates electricity from body heat by forcing thermal energy to flow sideways through thin films. According to ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.notebookcheck.net/Battery-free-watches-New-tech-uses-thin-films-to-generate-electricity-from-body-heat.789123.0.html","children":"NotebookCheck's report"}],", this isn't another theoretical concept — it's a practical approach to eliminating batteries in wearables entirely. The technology redirects heat flow laterally rather than vertically, allowing the entire device to remain paper-thin while harvesting energy from the temperature difference between your body and the environment. Early signals suggest this could enable a battery-free future for smart clothing and health monitors, categories that have historically struggled with power delivery. What's clever isn't just the physics — it's the form factor. Most thermoelectric generators are bulky vertical structures, making them impractical for anything you'd actually wear against your skin. The sideways approach could change that equation entirely."]}],"\n",["$","div",null,{"className":"not-prose my-8 pt-6 border-t border-white/10","children":[null,["$","div",null,{"className":"glass-card overflow-hidden mb-4 !hover:transform-none","children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/images/articles/body-heat-to-power-seoul-researchers-crack-battery/subtitle.jpg","alt":"What actually changes when your shirt powers itself","className":"w-full h-auto max-h-[400px] object-cover"}]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-text-secondary italic text-lg leading-relaxed font-medium","children":"What actually changes when your shirt powers itself"}]]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["The practical implications matter if the technology scales beyond the laboratory. Smart clothing has struggled to gain mainstream traction because nobody wants to charge their shirt or replace coin cells in their socks. A flat, self-sustaining power source removes that friction. But there are legitimate caveats. The research doesn't specify power output, and body heat harvesting has historically produced modest energy — microwatts, not milliwatts. For simple sensors tracking temperature or heart rate, that's sufficient. For a smartwatch with a bright display? Unlikely. The competitive landscape matters here. ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.samsung.com/wearables","children":"Samsung"}]," and ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.apple.com/watch","children":"Apple"}]," have both explored alternative power sources, but neither has cracked the battery problem for mainstream devices. ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.wareable.com/health-and-wellbeing/best-fitness-trackers","children":"Wearable health tech"}]," has always promised more than it delivers on the power front. If Seoul's thin-film approach delivers consistent power in real-world conditions, it could redirect where wearables go next — onto fabrics and skin patches rather than wrists. Most people don't need another glowing screen; they need unobtrusive health monitoring that works without intervention."]}]]}]
